title: 3 prep sports events to check out
text:
3 prep sports events to check out Scott A. Williams , Stevens Point Journal Media 1:03 p.m. CDT October 18, 2015 File photo. CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
Volleyball: WIAA Division 1 through 4 regional competition, 7 p.m., Tuesday/Thursday: Stevens Point area schools will look to extend their seasons when regional competition gets underway in all four divisions starting Tuesday in Divisions 2, 3 and 4. Rosholt hosts Saint Mary Catholic in one of five Division 3 regional openers involving area teams Tuesday. Amherst heads to CWC 8 rival Weyauwega-Fremont, while Iola-Scandinavia hits the road for a date with Shiocton in another CWC 8 matchup. Rounding out the opening-night matchups are Pacelli at Auburndale and Tri-County will take on Loyal/Granton in Loyal. In Division 4, Almond-Bancroft travels to Assumption on Tuesday to open tournament play. SPASH opens Division 1 play at home against Chippewa Falls on Thursday. 
Football: WIAA Division 1 through 7 Level 1 matchups, 7 p.m. Friday: Two of the four Stevens Point area teams to qualify for the playoffs — Amherst in Division 5 and Almond-Bancroft in Division 7 — earned No. 1 seeds in their respective eight-team brackets after finishing the regular season unbeaten. The top-ranked Falcons host New Holstein (5-4) looking for a return trip to the state title game, while the Eagles face a CWC 10 rematch with Port Edwards (5-4) at home. Meanwhile, SPASH (7-2), a No. 4 seed in Division 1, returns to the postseason after a one-year absence and hosts former Wisconsin Valley Conference rival D.C. Everest (5-4). Iola-Scandinavia (8-1) rounds out the area contingent as a No. 2 seed in Division 6 with a home date against Crivitz (5-4). 
Cross Country: WIAA Division 1 and 3 sectional meets, 4:30 a.m., Saturday, Standing Rocks Park, Stevens Point: Runners from all over central Wisconsin will vie for berths at the WIAA State Meet in Wisconsin Rapids on Nov. 1. The Top two teams for boys and girls in each division, along with the top five individuals not part of those qualifying teams, advance to The Ridges Golf Course. The SPASH boys and girls are coming off Wisconsin Valley Conference championships a week ago and are considered amnong the favorites in Division 1 to reach state. Adam Rzentkowski leads a strong Rosholt boys team in Division 3, while Amherst's Alyssa Niggemann, along with Erika Kisting and Leighten Fischer of Iola-Scandinavia, eye sectional titles.
